(40, 26, 14, 41, 14, 10, 11, 'went unto the chief priests', 'Connection of Judas''s Betrayal', 'Both passages emphasize Judas Iscariot''s role as one of the twelve disciples who conspires with the chief priests to betray Jesus. The mention of Judas going to the chief priests in both texts highlights his pivotal action in the betrayal narrative.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 14, 40, 26, 47, 47, 'one of the twelve', 'Judas''s Betrayal and Action', 'This connection highlights Judas Iscariot''s role as one of the twelve disciples in both passages. In the first, he approaches the chief priests, and in the second, he arrives with a multitude from them, indicating his betrayal.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 14, 43, 6, 70, 71, 'one of the twelve', 'Connection of Judas Iscariot', 'Both passages emphasize Judas Iscariot''s role as a betrayer among the twelve disciples. Matthew identifies Judas''s action of going to the chief priests, while John explicitly labels him as ''a devil'' who would betray Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 14, 43, 13, 2, 2, 'Judas Iscariot', 'Connection of Judas Iscariot', 'This connection highlights Judas Iscariot''s role in betrayal. Both passages mention Judas Iscariot, emphasizing his actions leading to the betrayal of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 14, 44, 1, 16, 16, 'Judas Iscariot', 'Connection Between Judas Passages', 'This connection highlights Judas Iscariot''s role in both passages. In Matthew, he is identified as one of the twelve who betrays Jesus, while Acts references him as the guide to those who took Jesus, fulfilling scripture.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 38, 11, 12, 13, 'thirty pieces of silver', 'Connection of Thirty Pieces of Silver', 'Both passages emphasize the thirty pieces of silver as the price for betrayal. This connection highlights the act of valuing a life at a low price, linking Judas''s betrayal to the prophetic imagery in Zechariah.', 'prophecy', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 1, 37, 26, 28, 'What will ye give me', 'Betrayal for Silver', 'This connection highlights the act of betrayal for monetary gain, as both passages depict the selling of a brother for silver. In Matthew, Judas betrays Jesus for thirty pieces of silver, while in Genesis, Joseph is sold by his brothers for twenty pieces of silver.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 2, 21, 32, 32, 'thirty pieces of silver', 'Connection of Thirty Pieces of Silver', 'This connection highlights the value of thirty pieces of silver in both passages. In Matthew, Judas betrays Jesus for this amount, while Exodus establishes it as compensation for harm done to a servant.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 54, 6, 9, 10, 'thirty pieces of silver', 'Connection of Money and Temptation', 'Both passages emphasize the dangers associated with money. In Matthew, Judas''s betrayal for ''thirty pieces of silver'' illustrates the corrupting influence of greed, while 1 Timothy warns that ''the love of money is the root of all evil.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 1, 38, 16, 16, NULL, 'Betrayal for Payment', 'Both passages emphasize a transaction for personal gain, with a focus on what will be given in exchange. The act of bargaining for a price highlights themes of betrayal and exploitation in human relationships.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 7, 16, 5, 5, 'thirty pieces of silver', 'Betrayal for Silver', 'This connection highlights the theme of betrayal for monetary gain. In both passages, individuals are motivated by the promise of silver to betray someone significant.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 15, 7, 17, 10, 10, 'thirty pieces of silver', 'Connection of Silver Payments', 'Both passages emphasize the exchange of silver for services. In Matthew, Judas receives thirty pieces of silver, while in Judges, Micah offers ten shekels of silver to the Levite. This connection highlights the transactional nature of loyalty and betrayal.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 16, 41, 14, 11, 11, 'sought opportunity to betray him', 'Betrayal of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Judas''s intention to betray Jesus. The phrases ''sought opportunity to betray him'' and ''sought how he might conveniently betray him'' highlight his active planning in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 16, 42, 22, 6, 6, 'sought opportunity to betray him', 'Betrayal of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the act of seeking opportunity to betray Jesus. The similarity in phrasing highlights the deliberate actions of Judas in both accounts.', 'parallel', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 42, 22, 7, 13, 'Where wilt thou that we prepare', 'Preparation for Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for the Passover meal. In Matthew, the disciples ask Jesus where to prepare, while in Luke, Jesus instructs Peter and John to prepare the Passover, highlighting the importance of this event.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 2, 12, 18, 20, 'the feast of unleavened bread', 'Passover and Unleavened Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of unleavened bread during the Passover. Matthew references the preparation for the Passover meal, which is rooted in the instructions given in Exodus regarding the consumption of unleavened bread.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 41, 14, 12, 16, 'Where wilt thou that we prepare for thee to eat the passover?', 'Preparation for Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for the Passover meal by the disciples. They inquire about where to prepare, indicating a shared narrative focus on this significant event.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 2, 12, 6, 6, 'prepare for thee to eat the passover', 'Passover Preparation Connection', 'This connection highlights the preparation for Passover in both passages. Matthew 26:17 mentions the disciples preparing for the Passover meal, while Exodus 12:6 outlines the timing for the Passover lamb''s sacrifice.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 3, 23, 5, 6, 'prepare for thee to eat the passover', 'Connection of Passover and Unleavened Bread', 'This connection highlights the timing of the Passover and the Feast of Unleavened Bread. Matthew 26:17 refers to the preparation for the Passover, which is directly linked to the observance outlined in Leviticus 23:5-6.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 4, 28, 16, 17, 'the feast of unleavened bread', 'Passover and Unleavened Bread', 'This connection highlights the timing of the Passover and the Feast of Unleavened Bread. Both passages emphasize the significance of the fourteenth day of the first month as the Passover, leading into the feast that follows.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 17, 5, 16, 1, 4, 'prepare for thee to eat the passover', 'Passover Observance Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of the Passover. Matthew 26:17 references the preparation for the Passover meal, while Deuteronomy 16:1-4 outlines the observance and significance of the Passover in remembrance of the Exodus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 41, 14, 13, 16, 'I will keep the passover at thy house', 'Preparation for the Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for the Passover meal. They describe the instructions given to the disciples to find a place for this significant event, highlighting the importance of the location and the timing.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 43, 7, 6, 6, 'My time is at hand', 'Timing of Jesus'' Mission', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing in Jesus'' ministry. In Matthew, Jesus indicates that ''My time is at hand,'' while in John, he states, ''My time is not yet come,'' emphasizing the differing perceptions of time regarding his mission.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 43, 13, 1, 1, 'My time is at hand', 'Connection of Jesus'' Hour', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of Jesus'' ''hour'' and the timing of the Passover. Matthew highlights the preparation for the Passover, while John reflects on Jesus'' awareness of his impending departure and love for his disciples.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 42, 22, 10, 13, 'I will keep the passover at thy house', 'Preparation for the Passover', 'Both passages emphasize the preparation for the Passover meal. They describe the instructions given to the disciples to find a place to eat the Passover with Jesus, highlighting the significance of this event.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 42, 22, 53, 53, 'My time is at hand', 'Power of Darkness and Timing', 'This connection highlights the theme of timing and the impending events surrounding Jesus'' fate. Both passages emphasize the significance of ''My time is at hand'' and ''this is your hour,'' indicating a pivotal moment in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 26, 18, 40, 21, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Instruction', 'Both passages emphasize the authority of the Lord''s commands. In Matthew 26:18, Jesus instructs his disciples about the Passover, while in Matthew 21:3, he directs them to retrieve a donkey, indicating his sovereign need.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
